Text: The initial stages of making the groups for each project started off smoothly, but then encountered a few speed bumps.
Around 30 minutes of the group allocation process was used by some people to try andÂ  convince others to join them in a project that didn't have much buy-in.
It was interesting to see how some people will work with others to form groups, while others will push their personal opinions to a point of trying to influence others in teaming up with them.
To add to the confusion, there was an error in the preference sheet, with some peoples preferences being completely different to what was on the sheet.
So we had to figure out who wanted what projects and then tried to balance the male/female ratio.
If the error in the preference sheet was designed on purpose, it definitely made us work harder!.
We had a team zoom meeting on Thursday morning, with everyone going over questions they wanted to ask and figuring out what we could do before the meeting.

There were times in the meeting where we were focused on topics that may have been too detailed for getting a general understanding of the problem, but it was probably better to try and get everyone's thoughts flowing freely to get a better understanding of how everyone saw the project.
The people in my group are quite motivated and seem to want to learn as much as possible.
They are also quick to offer help, so I'm optimistic that we can do well on the project.
There are some differences in personality, but I think there is enough respect among the team members that any issues will be able to be solved without getting out of hand.
My goals for the project are to learn some new skills and help the team as much as I can.
There is some unease in the back of my mind, as I'm not sure if what I've learnt can be of any use for the project.
After talking to some of my classmates, it seems everyone is feeling the same way.
I'm thinking the best way forward will to try to be positive, work hard and not be a perfectionist and the outcome will sort itself out.
